article.description: In their second game under new coach Hubie Brown, the Grizzlies remained the NBA's only winless team, suffering a 111-93 loss to the Chicago Bulls.
article.headline: Grizzlies 0-2 under Brown, 0-10 overall
article.linkText: Bulls' Marshall comes off bench to light up Grizzlies
article.story:
CHICAGO (AP) -- Hubie Brown didn't expect to be a quick fix for the Memphis Grizzlies.
Marshall

Donyell Marshall scored 31 points and had 17 rebounds off the bench, and Jalen Rose also had 31 points as the Chicago Bulls beat the Memphis Grizzlies 111-93 on Saturday night. Memphis remained the NBA's only winless team at 0-10, and fell to 0-2 since Brown took over as coach. "It's difficult for them, for us,'' Brown said. "It's the fourth day we've been together and we're supposed to beat the Bulls on the road. You can see why they beat New Orleans and New Jersey.'' Eddy Curry scored 10 of his 14 points in the first quarter, Jay Williams added 12 and Tyson Chandler 11 for the Bulls. Chicago bounced back from a 105-87 loss to New Orleans on Friday night. "We did a good job of responding after last night,'' Rose said. "Any time you play like we did last night you wonder how the team is going to come out.'' Jason Williams scored 18 points, and Wesley Person and Pau Gasol both had 14 for the Grizzlies. Chicago went on a 19-6 run during the second quarter to give the Bulls a 48-30 lead. Marshall scored 13 during the span and had 15 in the quarter. He started the run with a breakaway dunk with a 11:06 in the quarter and ended it on a 3-pointer from the corner with 5:35 remaining in the quarter. "Last night, I did not come out and play well,'' Marshall said. "I know not to give up. We have 82 games in this league and we have to come out and play hard every night out. The good thing about NBA basketball is that you can come back the next night.'' Memphis got within four in the third quarter when Gasol converted on an alley-oop to make it 70-66, but Chicago answered with a 12-2 run to end the quarter. Rose hit a 3-pointer and had a three-point play during the run to give the Bulls an 82-68 lead to end the third quarter.

Game notes
Bulls head coach Bill Cartwright played five seasons (1982-87) under Brown with the Knicks. ... The Bulls improved to 4-6 on the season, the team's best record after 10 games since being 6-4 on Nov. 15, 1998. ... The last time two Bulls players scored 30 or more points in a game was March 22, 1998, when Michael Jordan and Scottie Pippen each scored 33.
